\par CREATING POTIONS
\par }{\fs20\cf0 The creator of a potion needs a level working 
surface and at least a few containers in which to mix liquids, as well as a source of heat to boil the brew. In addition, he needs ingredients. The costs for materials and ingredients are subsumed in the cost for brewing the potion\emdash 25 gp x\u-4064
\'3f the level of the spell x \u-4064\'3fthe level of the caster.
\par All ingredients and materials used to brew a potion must be fresh and unused. The character must pay the full cost for brewing each potion. (Economies of scale do not apply.)
\par The imbiber of the potion is both the caster and the target. Spells with a range of personal cannot be made into potions.
\par The creator must have prepared the spell to be placed in the potion (or must know the spell, in the case of a sorcerer or bard) and must provide any material component or focus the spell requires.
\par If casting the spell would reduce the caster\rquote s XP total, he pays the XP cost upon beginning the brew in addition to the XP cost for making the potion itself. Material components are consumed when he begins working, but a focus is not. (A 
focus used in brewing a potion can be reused.) The act of brewing triggers the prepared spell, making it unavailable for casting until the character has rested and regained spells. (That is, that spell slot is expended from his currently prepared spells, 
just as if it had been cast.) Brewing a potion requires one day.
\par Item Creation Feat Required: Brew Potion.
